1 Business Statement

There is a strong correlation between water usage and the weather in the water industry. Water usage increases during warmer and drier periods, and when its colder and wetter, water usage is typically less. Jordan Valley Water Conservancy District (JVWCD) has noticed this trend and is wanting to find a solution that will allow them to be more proactive instead of reactive with these seasonal trends.

Historically, operations staff have worked in a reactive state chasing water demands of community members, which is influenced by changing weather. Most of this variability happens in the summer, with residential outdoor landscape watering being the leading consumer. Roughly 65% of the communitys water use is in that outdoor landscape space. This reactive chase ensures that the community always has water, which often requires water managers, supervisors and operators to spend long hours (including overtime hours), watching and reacting to changes in water demand. Managing the systems water demand can be like steering a large ship sudden and abrupt changes are not easily absorbed. Also, there is a cost factor to this. Well-informed planning to operate the system with consistency and minor tweaks saves money. However, operational costs can add up quickly if a well is started at an unplanned time. This event could cost the water system $5,000 to $9,000 in electricity demand charges alone.

JVWCD would like to be more efficient with its resources and manpower. The goal of this capstone project is to explore modeling water demand against weather data. The ideal outcome of this project would be a predictive model that gives the operations team more confidence in making decisions related to water demand so that they can move to a more proactive form of water deliveries.

2 Analytic Objectives

System demand is calculated by adding all the individual sources and subtracting the reservoir trends from the total. JVWCD has provided system data to use for modeling. This is time series data and could require some cleaning before use in a model.

JVWCD is currently using the online version of Tableau. It would be ideal if we had a model that could be used there so as to reduce the amount of training it would take to implement this model. JVWCD pays for 30 licenses of Tableau Online.

One aspect of the analytics problem is selecting a weather service to provide weather data. The one that stands out to us right now is openweathermap.org and wed likely get the information we need from the free version but are also looking at other options to compare against. The team will look at two additional sources of weather data to benchmark against the desired version (openweathermap.org).

3 Exploratory Questions

The questions below were crafted prior to our EDA. We used these questions to help guide our EDA and added to it during our EDA.

Is there strong correlations between the different weather metrics and the different point type? Do we see a seasonal trend with the data? Can the weather help predict demand? How does weather change season by season? Is there anything useful with hourly data vs.daily weather data? How does demand change from month to month? Is there a correlation between demand and temperature, and how strong is that correlation? What are the best predictor variables to help predict daily demand? Seasonal variation?

4.2 Read CSV files and pre process

#read in data. Change names to be more readable and make hourly demand numeric
sd <- read.csv("2_year_system_demand.csv")%>%
  rename('hourly_demand' = 'Hourly.Demand..cfs.',
         'date_time' = 'Read.Date.Time')%>%
  mutate(hourly_demand = as.numeric(hourly_demand),
         hourly_demand = ifelse(is.na(hourly_demand),0,hourly_demand)) 

#Make Date and Time match a consistent format with the Weather Data
sd2 <- as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sd$date_time, " ", 3))%>%
  rename(date = V1, time = V2, am_or_pm = V3)%>%
  mutate(datetime_str = paste(date, time, am_or_pm),
         datetime = as.POSIXct(strptime(datetime_str, format = "%m/%d/%y %I:%M %p")),
         datetime_military = strftime(datetime, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M")) %>%
  select(datetime,datetime_military)
sd3 <-as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sd2$datetime_military, " ", 2))%>%
  rename(date = V1, time = V2)
sd4 <-as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sd3$date, "/", 3))%>%
  rename(CalendarMonth = V1,  CalendarDay = V2, CalendarYear = V3)
#Throw it all together
sd <- cbind(sd,sd2,sd3,sd4)%>%
  select(-date_time)
#Get rid of temp dfs
remove(sd2,sd3,sd4)

#The names and dates in this table do not need much conversion
wa <- read.csv("weather_sl_airport.csv")
  
  

sp <- read.csv("system_demand_by_point_type.csv")%>%
  rename('date_time' = 'Read.Date.Time',
         'well_flow_cfs' = 'Well.Flow..cfs.',
         'purchased_flow_cfs' = 'Purchased.Flow..cfs.',
         'transported_flow_cfs' = 'Transported.Flow..cfs.',
         'treated_flow_cfs' = 'Treated.Flow..cfs.',
         'injected_flow_cfs' = 'Injected.Flow..cfs.',
         'reservoir_trend_cfs' = 'Reservoir.Trend..cfs.',)
#Make Date and Time match a consistant format with the Weather Data
sp2 <- as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sp$date_time, " ", 3))%>%
  rename(date = V1, time = V2, am_or_pm = V3)%>%
  mutate(datetime_str = paste(date, time, am_or_pm),
         datetime = as.POSIXct(strptime(datetime_str, format = "%m/%d/%y %I:%M %p")),
         datetime_military = strftime(datetime, format = "%m/%d/%Y %H:%M")) %>%
  select(datetime,datetime_military)
sp3 <-as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sp2$datetime_military, " ", 2))%>%
  rename(date = V1, time = V2)
sp4 <-as.data.frame(str_split_fixed(sp3$date, "/", 3))%>%
  rename(CalendarMonth = V1,  CalendarDay = V2, CalendarYear = V3)
#Throw it all together
sp <- cbind(sp,sp2,sp3,sp4)%>%
  mutate(reservoir_trend_cfs = as.numeric(reservoir_trend_cfs))%>%
  select(-date_time)
#Get rid of temp dfs
remove(sp2,sp3,sp4)

4.6 A Different Merge of the Data

#Weather data begins prior to 2020 where the system data begins. Truncate for merging
merweth=wa %>% 
  filter(CalendarYear>=2020)
#Date column is a character. Convert to date
merweth=merweth %>% 
  mutate(WeatherDate = as.Date(WeatherDate,format="%m/%d/%Y"))
#Date column is in POSIXct format. Convert to date
mersd=sd %>% 
  mutate(ActualDate = as.Date(paste(as.numeric(sd$CalendarMonth),
                                    as.numeric(sd$CalendarDay),
                                    as.numeric(sd$CalendarYear),
                                    sep="-"),
                                    format="%m-%d-%Y"))
#Change hourly_demand to avg_daily demand for merge
mershrink=mersd %>% 
  group_by(ActualDate) %>% 
  summarize(avgdaily_demand = mean(hourly_demand))

#remove NA at the bottom
mershrink=mershrink[1:731,] 


#Merge Datasets
merginated = merge(mershrink,merweth,by.x = "ActualDate",
                   by.y = "WeatherDate",all.y = TRUE,
                   all.x = FALSE)

5.1 Hourly Demand Histogram

ggplot(sd,aes(hourly_demand))+
  geom_histogram()+
  theme_minimal()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

For each of these histograms the x axis is the hourly demand value and the y axis is how many times that value occured. Demand seems to be heavily skewed towards the lower numbers.

5.2 Hourly Demand Histogram by Calendar Month

ggplot(sd,aes(hourly_demand))+
  geom_histogram()+
  theme_minimal()+
  facet_wrap(~CalendarMonth)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

It would apear that the distribution of hourly demand numbers changes a lot from month to mont.

ggplot(sd,aes(hourly_demand))+

The difference between 2020 and 2021 dont seem very notable.This is super interesting considering 2021 was considered a major drought year. Does look like the demand in 2021 was a bit higher surprisingly.

5.5 Average Hourly Demand

sd%>%
  group_by(Hour)%>%
  summarise(mean(hourly_demand))%>%
  rename(avg_demand = 'mean(hourly_demand)')%>%
  ggplot(aes(Hour, avg_demand))+
  geom_col()+
  theme_minimal()

Demand seems to drop towards the middle of the day. This makes sense as people typically water laws and such during the early morning hours.

5.6 Average Hourly Demand by Season

sd%>%
  group_by(season,Hour)%>%
  summarise(mean(hourly_demand))%>%
  rename(avg_demand = 'mean(hourly_demand)')%>%
  ggplot(aes(Hour, avg_demand))+
  geom_col()+
  theme_minimal()+
  facet_wrap(~season)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'season'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

Seems like the Demand is higher in the summer as expected and seems to be higher earlier in the day. Aain could be due to lawn care.

#Create ISO week number identifier column
merginated = merginated %>% 
  mutate(weeknum = ISOweek(ActualDate))
#Create list to show precipitation for a given ISO week number
weekref = merginated %>% 
  group_by(weeknum) %>% 
  summarize(weekfall = sum(Precipitation))
#Visualize
weekref %>% 
  ggplot(aes(weeknum,weekfall))+
  geom_col()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90))+
  ggtitle("Precipitation by Week Number")

#Seems a bit sporadic

#shift column so that list shows prior week precipitation
weekref = shift.column(weekref,columns = "weekfall",len = 1L,up=TRUE)
weekref = weekref[,c(1,3)]
weekref = weekref %>% 
  rename(prevweekfall = weekfall.Shifted)
#Merge list to create column showing rainfall by previous week
Merged_Data_Prevweek = merge(merginated,weekref,by.x = "weeknum",by.y = "weeknum",all.y = TRUE,all.x = TRUE)

9 Results and Conclusions

During this EDA we discovered that are initial assumption holds true. Temperature plays an important role in water usage. There is more demand on hotter days and seasons when there isnt precipitation. We can see that there are correlations between daily demand and Temperature Mean, Min, and Max, CoolingDegreeDays, SnowDepth, Precipitation, and Snowfall. The weather data available currently only tracks metrics on a daily basis. The data received from JVWCD tracks demand minute by minute.We then merged and aggregated the data to fit our needs. We ran a linear regression where we discovered that the previous week precipitation is significant along with temperature and therefore seasons.Additionally, we see how the different point types are affected by the weather data as well and there overall distribution. How initial goal is to successfully predict daily demand and then see how that compares with the necessary point types.

10 Questions for Jordan Valley

  • Difference in weather and water granularity?

  • Could you please explain the types of flows?

  • What do we do with NULLs?

  • What do we do with negative hourly demand values?

  • Missing hourly entries?

  • If a lot of this data makes logical sense (meaning we can generally predict demand based on past data and an upcoming weather forecast), what additional value is Jordan Valley looking for in a prediction model?
